# Checkpoint discipline (agent-checkpoint MCP)

This project uses the `agent-checkpoint` MCP server so work survives session
cuts (context limits, quota). Follow these rules:

## On task start
If the task could be a continuation of earlier work (or you are unsure), call
`get_checkpoint` FIRST. If a checkpoint exists, resume from "what remains" —
do NOT redo anything listed under "what was already done".

## While working
Call `save_checkpoint` after EVERY concrete sub-task, not only when a numbered
step finishes. A sub-task is: a file created or edited, a test passing, a
command run successfully, a bug diagnosed. If the session died right now,
the checkpoint must be enough for another agent to continue without asking.

When calling `save_checkpoint`:
- `plan`: the full numbered plan, verbatim, every time.
- `what_was_done`: cumulative and specific ("created src/auth.py with login()
  and logout(); tests in tests/test_auth.py pass"), never vague ("made progress").
- `what_remains`: the exact next action in the current step ("wire login()
  into routes.py POST /login; then run pytest tests/test_auth.py").

## On task completion
Save a final checkpoint with `step_status="done"` and the current step equal
to the total. Ask the user before calling `clear_checkpoints` with
`confirm=true`.
